Cheung Kong, China Unicom, Prada: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-09-20T00:38:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-20/cheung-kong-china-unicom-prada-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  declined 2.8 percent to 18,917.95. The
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, dropped 3.7 percent to 9,866.97.  Cheung Kong  (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK): The real-estate company
controlled by billionaire  Li Ka-shing  plans to bid for the
residential and commercial development at the Nam Cheong MTR
station project, the Ming Pao Daily News reported, citing
Executive Director Justin Chiu.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16
HK) also plans to bid for the project, which is valued at HK$16
billion, according to the report. Cheung Kong sank 4.1 percent
to HK$96.75. Sun Hung Kai fell 2.2 percent to HK$100.90.  China Coal Energy Co. (1898 HK): The country’s second-
largest coal producer said it will begin safety inspections of
its underground mines in Shanxi province after the company’s
parent halted production in the region following a fatal mine
accident. The suspension is “short-term” and won’t have
“material impact” on the operation of the company, it said.
China Coal tumbled 17 percent to HK$8.26 before trading was
suspended yesterday. The stock will resume trading today.  China Unicom ( Hong Kong ) Ltd. (762 HK): The nation’s
second-biggest mobile phone carrier said it added 2.36 million
new mobile phone users last month, compared to 2.13 million
users in July. The stock lost 0.7 percent to HK$16.74.  China Shipping Container Lines Co. (2866 HK): The country’s
second-largest carrier of sea-cargo boxes by sales had its
rating cut to “hold” from “buy” at BNP Paribas. The
brokerage lowered its share-price forecast by 42 percent to
HK$1.67 on expectations freight rates will decline. China
Shipping slumped 5.8 percent to HK$1.47.  Prada SpA (1913 HK): The Italian maker of  luxury goods  said
first-half net income increased to 179.5 million euros ($244.5
million), compared with 103 million a year earlier. The shares
sank 3.7 percent to HK$41.30.  To contact the reporter on this story:
